ld English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’), hence a nickname for someone with white hair or a pale complexion. In some cases it is perhaps from a Middle English survival of the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i>, a short form of names in <i>Hwīt-</i> (from <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’). The name may also be topographic, referring to someone who lived by a bend or curve in a river or road (from Old English <i>wiht</i> ‘bend’), the source of the placename of Great Whyte in Ramsey, Huntingdonshire (compare   Wight  ). This name is also a variant of   Wight  . The surname <i>White</i> is also very common among African Americans.","Irish and Scottish: adopted for any of several Irish and Scottish Gaelic names based on <i>bán</i> ‘white, fair’ (see   Bain   1,   McElwain  ) or <i>fionn</i> ‘fair’ (see   Finn   1). The English surname has been Gaelicized in Ireland as <b>de Faoite</b>.","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘white’, for example German   Weiss  , French   Blanc  , Polish <b>Białas</b> (see   Bialas  ), Slovenian   Belec  , or any other synonymous Slavic surname beginning with <i>Bel-</i>, <i>Bev-</i>, <i>Biel-</i> or <i>Bil-</i>."]}]},{"name":"Benjamin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the youngest of the twelve sons of Jacob. His mother Rachel died in giving birth to him, and in her last moments she named him <i>Benoni</i>, meaning ‘son of my sorrow’. His father, however, did not wish him to bear such an ill-omened name, and renamed him <i>Benyamin</i> (Genesis 35:16–18; 42:4). This means either ‘son of the right hand’ or more likely ‘son of the south’ (Hebrew <i>yamin</i> can also mean ‘south’), since Benjamin was the only child of Jacob born in Canaan and not in Mesopotamia to the north. Another tradition is that the second element of the name is a variant of the Hebrew plural noun <i>yamim</i>, which means ‘days’ but is used idiomatically to mean ‘year’ or ‘years’. The name would then mean ‘son of (my) old age’ and refer to the fact that Benjamin was Jacob's youngest child. In the Middle Ages the name was often given to sons whose mothers had died in childbirth. Today it has no such unfortunate associations and it grew enormously in popularity following the release of the film The Graduate (  1967 ), in which  Dustin Hoffman  played the role of  Benjamin Braddock . It is used in Scotland as an Anglicized form of Gaelic Beathan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705205,"age":9,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":11,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":40,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":60,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705213,"age":82,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Benjamin Whitson was born in 1560, in Mildenhall, Suffolk, England. He married Cathy Cox in 1579, in Mildenhall, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1560–":"1560–Surnud","1564–Female":"1564–Surnud","1580–1640":"1580–1640","1560–Male":"1560–Surnud","1569":"1569","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1564":"1564","1651":"1651","1640":"1640","1560":"1560","1571":"1571","1580":"1580","Mildenhall, Forest Heath Dstrict, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1560–":"1560–Kuollut","1564–Female":"1564–Kuollut","1580–1640":"1580–1640","1560–Male":"1560–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1564":"1564","1651":"1651","1640":"1640","1560":"1560","1571":"1571","1580":"1580","Mildenhall, Forest Heath Dstrict, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1560–":"1560–Décédé","1564–Female":"1564–Décédée","